wcg_diff_general: Before reading the story, most of my thoughts were completely random- only related to the previous word I typed. After reading the story, I started to type words that related to the actions, settings, or characters that were included in the story.
wcg_strategy: Whenever I thought of one word, I tried to think of other words that were related to it in some way. Like typing 'cod' after 'fish.'
guess_experiment: I think this experiment is trying to see how people's thoughts are affected by the material they read. For example, with the word chain, it's trying to see what words come to mind after reading the story, and with the "part 2," it's trying to see if people immediately assume the unrelated story is a continuation of the first, despite the content not matching whatsoever. I think the added part of 'this is a continuation' is just meant to confuse people and see who believes it's right after seeing what the story of "part 2" is.
volition_explanation: I didn't experience anything too noteworthy. I was just really interested in how the story would play out, so naturally I was thinking about what could possible happen later on. I used aspects of the story in the following word chain game because I thought it'd be fun and a good way to remember what I read.
wcg_diff_explanation: The only change I felt besides the switch in topic was just my overall intrigue with the word chain. Before reading the story, I just treated it as a fun game to challenge how fast I could think and type, but after reading, I started to think more of the story than the actual task at hand. I wanted to continue reading, so I instead used the word chain as a way to reflect on the material. Eventually, I started to run out of words that related to the story, at least words that immediately came to mind. It was still a fun activity though.
interference_explanation: I was trying to see how this story was a continuation of the last one I read, I even assumed that the narrator for the second part was Stuart from part 1. Since I was so focused on trying to connect dots, the ending caught me off guard and made me smile because of the humor that came from it. The revelation towards the end kept me from being dissatisfied that it had nothing to do with part 1.
volition_interference_explanation: The purple story didn't linger in my head like the first one, I don't even remember a word chain appearing after the second story, so I didn't have the chance to even let it influence my choice in words. It was a very funny story though.
open_box: This study was very entertaining! Thank you for introducing me to Carver's book, it had me hooked :)

It was a subtle but unsettling shift, like seeing familiar things in a new, darker light.

guess_experiment: This experiment appears to be measuring reading comprehension, attention to detail, and the ability to recall specific information from a narrative. By asking multiple-choice questions about the story’s events, characters, and details, it assesses how well the reader understands and retains information.
